Comments: Richardson has shown more as a passer than many expected, and Shane Steichen is giving him plenty of rushing and GL opportunities.
There's not much to love about a Zach Wilson-led Jets offense, but Hall has shown elite RB1 upside as soon as he's 100% healthy.
Chase is still an elite WR long term, but there's concern about 2023 production if Burrow's calf isn't 100% all season.
The only concern for Tua is health. If he can stay on the field, Tua will be a strong QB1 with elite weekly upside this season.
Burrow will be fine in the long run, but there's a chance that this calf injury could greatly limit his 2023 production.
The age cliff is looming for McCaffrey, but he's a weekly top-3 RB if he can stay healthy for the duration of the 2023 season.
CHI has finally started to call more designed runs for him, so Fields remains a QB1 ROS even with inconsistent passing.
Wilson moves down slightly due to the QB downgrade in 2023, but he's still seeing a massive target share this year and is fine long-term.
Age be damned. My dynasty rankings align more with redraft in-season, and Hill and Diggs are still elite WR1s and league-winners in 2023.
There was some concern that Garoppolo wouldn't target Adams downfield, but Adams has been a dominant force and truly QB-proof.
Stroud has looked poised from the moment he stepped on an NFL field. Even without much rushing upside, he could quickly ascend.
Pollard is seeing lead back and GL usage and is a top-5 RB for 2023, but keep in mind he's on the franchise tag heading into 2024.
Ekeler should remain a top-12 RB once he returns from his ankle injury, but he's a declining asset who will be 29 years old next season.
Prescott has been inconsistent to start the year, and he may not need to throw much in general with DAL's defense limiting opponents.
Watson still hasn't shaken off the rust despite playing behind a top OL, and it's unclear whether he'll regain his HOU form at this point.
JSN is only playing in 3WR sets and being targeted on short routes, but his outlook remains bullish long-term.
Flowers has already ascended to the clear No. 1 WR role in BAL, and things should open up downfield once their OL gets healthier.
Addison is slowing taking over the No. 2 WR role in MIN, and their defense is forcing enough shootouts to give him a ton of targets.
London still looks like an elite prospect long-term, but Ridder is awful. It's hard to see London being more than a WR3 in 2023.
As with Chase, there's significant worry that Burrow's calf will downgrade the entire CIN offense in fantasy.
Achane will likely lead a committee backfield, but McDaniel's scheme puts him in position to score a TD every time he touches the ball.
It's become apparent that Gibbs's fantasy ceiling will be limited by DET's clear preference for Montgomery on early downs and near the GL.
It's unclear how many games Taylor will play in 2023, but he should still be a strong buy for rebuilding teams.
Samuel and Aiyuk may alternate big weeks in 2023, but both have massive ceilings with Aiyuk heading to free agency this offseason.
Even as a rookie, LaPorta is heavily involved as a pass-catcher and has shown high-end playmaking ability.
ARI's offense has been surprisingly efficient with Dobbs at the helm, and Brown is seeing enough volume to be a WR2 ROS.
Even with Kupp's impending return, Nacua has shown route-running savvy and rapport with Stafford to remain a strong WR2 ROS.
Purdy may not have elite QB1 upside distributing the ball in Shanahan's run-heavy offense, but he can be a perennial back-end QB1.
This may be Cousins's last season of fantasy relevance in MIN, but he's a solid back-end QB1 for contending teams ROS yet again.
It's still early, but 2023 looks like a lost season for the 1st overall pick without a major upgrade in receiving weapons or playcalling.
There's no weekly floor or ceiling with Ridder. Perhaps Heinicke could be better, but Pitts probably won't hit until 2024, if at all.
Goff looks to be in command of this DET offense and should be a solid QB2 behind this OL and with these pass-catching playmakers.
Love doesn't look elite, but he can be a perennial back-end QB1 in Matt LaFleur's scheme, especially if GB's OL gets healthy.
There's risk with Allen nearing 32 years old, but he looks to be a strong WR2 with WR1 upside ROS for contending teams.
There will be growing pains with Richardson at QB, but Pittman looks to be heavily involved in Steichen's passing offense.
Jordan Love has looked adequate enough to execute LaFleur's offense with efficiency. Watson could be a strong contributor once healthy.
Stroud has started off strong and should continue to improve, which gives Collins WR2 potential ROS with high weekly upside.
Moore showed his massive weekly ceiling vs. poor DEN and WAS secondaries and can be a WR2 ROS.
Ridley has been quiet the last few games since exploding in Week 1, but he should bounce back and has WR2 potential ROS.
It's only been one week back, but Kamara looks like a RB1 ROS for contending teams with Derek Carr's proficiency for checking down.
Montgomery looks to be a strong RB2 ROS with weekly TD potential behind a stout DET OL that wants to run the ball, especially near the GL.
Meyers has shown immense PPR upside with Garoppolo in the Edelman role in McDaniels's offense and continues to be undervalued.
BUF has wanted Allen to run a bit less, and a healthy Davis has been a great downfield target. He's a boom/bust WR3 ROS.
Swift has cemented himself as the lead back in PHI, but he's still a risky asset given his injury history. Hold if contending but sell if possible.
Both Williams and Ford could be easily replaced, but they look to be near workhorses for now and project as RB2s with RB1 upside ROS.
Henry is running behind a bottom-5 OL and is losing snaps and passing downs to Spears. Sell high if possible after a big game vs. CIN.
Howell has been inconsistent but looks to be a serviceable QB2 ROS with some rushing upside.
Stafford is playing well and could be a top-12 fantasy QB ROS once he gets Kupp back alongside Nacua. He's a cheap buy for contenders.
DEN's defense is the worst in the NFL, but their offense has been much improved under Payton. Wilson is a solid QB2 ROS.
With ARSB and LaPorta playing well, Williams is a sell-high if he has a big game once back from the suspension.
Mims has shown flashes but seems unlikely to be a consistent contributor as a rookie. He's a hold or buy heading into 2024.
Sell Sanders if possible. He's looked inefficient and could be battling this groin issue all year. Hubbard could become the 1A at some point.
Prescott continues to target Ferguson heavily, and Schultz was a back-end TE1 in that role. Ferguson remains a strong hold or buy.
Mostert can still have some big weeks if he stays healthy, but Achane looks to be the 1A in MIA's backfield going forward.
There's a real chance that TEN could trade Derrick Henry if they fall out of contention, which would give Spears weekly RB2 potential.
Moss is a hold for now. There's still no telling what will happen with Taylor ROS, and Moss has been a workhorse with Taylor out.
Dobbs is the 2023 Geno Smith. He's played exceptionally well and should earn a starting role somewhere next year, even if it's not in ARI.
Garoppolo has actually played well to open the year and is a serviceable QB2 ROS if healthy throwing to Adams and Meyers.
Dell has played well outside despite his size and clearly has chemistry with Stroud to make big plays downfield. He's a decent flex ROS.
It's possible that no KC WR emerges to be a true No. 1 option in this offense, but Toney is the most dynamic KC WR if he can stay healthy.
Both Doubs and Reed have flashed, but it's possible neither will see consistent targets with Watson back. Both are holds for now.
Jones has shown playmaking ability when healthy and can be a boom/bust flex play if JAX can get it together on offense.
It's looking like Bateman is the No. 3 option behind Andrews and Flowers even when healthy, and he hasn't been healthy very much.
Dowdle has shown some playmaking potential and could have RB2 upside if Pollard were to miss any time.
It sounds like Rodgers doesn't plan to retire and should be back for the start of the 2024 season.
Wilson should return from IR soon but will need Achane or Mostert to miss time to be startable in fantasy.
Williams should be ready for Week 1 of 2024, and the ACL shouldn't affect a straight-line downfield threat like him as much as other WRs.
Dillon didn't show much when Jones was out early in the season and doesn't look to have much upside even if Jones were to miss more time.
Elijah Mitchell is continually banged up, so Mason has a chance to be fantasy relevant if McCaffrey were to miss any time ROS.
It's possible that neither of these RBs will ever be fantasy relevant again, but they're worth rolling the dice on for a late 3rd or less.
